1
00:00:06,560 --> 00:00:08,880
(LEAVES RUSTLING)

2
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:13,560
(PANTING)

3
00:00:23,840 --> 00:00:25,440
(CREAKING)

4
00:00:42,160 --> 00:00:44,000
I'm lost. Please, can you help me?

5
00:00:44,880 --> 00:00:46,480
It's that way.

6
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:52,000
-Are those trees?
-I need the Doctor.

7
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:53,760
Are you the Doctor?

8
00:00:54,040 --> 00:00:57,400
Yes. Do you have an appointment?

9
00:00:57,640 --> 00:00:59,680
You need an appointment
to see the Doctor.

10
00:01:00,840 --> 00:01:02,840
Please. Something's chasing me.

11
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:08,600
(DOOR CLOSES)

12
00:01:09,240 --> 00:01:10,600
(GASPING)

13
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:13,920
When you drink a glass of Coke,
it's only this big

14
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:16,040
but it's actually got
this much sugar in it.

15
00:01:16,320 --> 00:01:18,200
-Works a bit like that.
-What does?

16
00:01:18,280 --> 00:01:19,920
The Tardis.

17
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:23,040
It's bigger on the inside
than the outside.

18
00:01:23,120 --> 00:01:24,280
Or did you not notice?

19
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:26,960
I just thought it was supposed to be
bigger on the inside,

20
00:01:27,040 --> 00:01:28,560
so I didn't say anything.

21
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:30,480
Well, of course it's supposed
to be bigger.

22
00:01:31,480 --> 00:01:33,200
Most people are confused by that.

23
00:01:33,520 --> 00:01:37,360
I find everything confusing, nearly.
So I don't say anything.

24
00:01:37,440 --> 00:01:38,880
That's how come I'm in the woods.

25
00:01:38,960 --> 00:01:40,760
I thought Miss Oswald told me
to find the Doctor,

26
00:01:41,160 --> 00:01:42,440
but it wasn't her.

27
00:01:42,520 --> 00:01:45,280
-It was just in my head.
-Miss Oswald? Dark hair?

28
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:47,920
Highly unpredictable?
Surprisingly round face?

29
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:50,720
Everyone says she's in love
with Mr Pink.

30
00:01:51,280 --> 00:01:52,520
The PE teacher?

31
00:01:52,600 --> 00:01:55,920
Maths. I really like him.
I was in his group.

32
00:01:56,160 --> 00:01:58,520
Mr Pink was looking after you?
Well, that explains why you're lost.

33
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:01,640
It doesn't surprise you
that I know all about your school?

34
00:02:01,720 --> 00:02:04,880
Everyone seems to know everything
about everything, apart from me.

35
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:07,000
-(BEEPING)
-That's not quite true.

36
00:02:07,080 --> 00:02:09,880
I, for instance, have no idea why,
when the terrestrial navigation...

37
00:02:10,840 --> 00:02:12,560
...the terrestrial navigation starts up,

38
00:02:12,640 --> 00:02:14,320
it closes down all the other systems.

39
00:02:14,840 --> 00:02:16,560
You should ask somebody who knows.

40
00:02:16,640 --> 00:02:19,960
Hmm. That's another of the drawbacks
of being the last of your species.

41
00:02:20,040 --> 00:02:22,240
No one to ask
when your Tardis won't start.

42
00:02:23,400 --> 00:02:25,200
(WHOOSHING)

43
00:02:26,480 --> 00:02:28,200
FEMALE ELECTRONIC VOICE:
You have reached your destination.

44
00:02:28,280 --> 00:02:30,400
No, we haven't. We're supposed
to be in the middle of London.

45
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:33,720
-You have reached your destination.
-Oh, stop saying that!

46
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:36,840
She's only saying it because it's true.

47
00:02:37,280 --> 00:02:39,200
We are in the middle of London.

48
00:02:39,480 --> 00:02:41,400
We are in the middle of a forest.

49
00:02:41,880 --> 00:02:43,040
Come and see.

50
00:02:45,280 --> 00:02:47,400
Nelson's Column. Do you like it?

51
00:02:47,480 --> 00:02:49,400
Do I... Sorry, what?

52
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:51,400
Do you like the forest
being in Trafalgar Square?

53
00:02:51,480 --> 00:02:52,920
I think it's lovely.

54
00:03:14,440 --> 00:03:17,040
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

55
00:04:11,840 --> 00:04:15,160
Bradley! Sir! Tell him, sir!
He's blinding me.

56
00:04:15,600 --> 00:04:17,680
-Give me that, Bradley.
-I'm allowed a torch, sir.

57
00:04:17,920 --> 00:04:20,120
I've got a note. I'm darkness-phobic.

58
00:04:20,200 --> 00:04:21,360
Just 'cause he's scared
of the dark, sir,

59
00:04:21,440 --> 00:04:23,120
does that mean
he's allowed to blind me?

60
00:04:23,200 --> 00:04:26,400
You're allowed a torch, Bradley,
not a pocket supernova.

61
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:27,520
Okay, listen up.

62
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,600
Just a few things to run through
before we head home.

63
00:04:29,680 --> 00:04:31,600
Put your phone away, Bradley.
Thank you.

64
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:34,240
Firstly, collect up any rubbish
you may have generated

65
00:04:34,320 --> 00:04:35,720
through midnight feasts or whatever...

66
00:04:37,480 --> 00:04:38,640
DANNY: Hello?

67
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:43,640
Hello?

68
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:49,080
GIRL: Look at this.

69
00:04:49,160 --> 00:04:51,400
Why's this one so fat, miss?

70
00:04:52,200 --> 00:04:54,280
Because it was alive so long.

71
00:04:54,760 --> 00:04:56,160
This ring, though.

72
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:57,560
All the other rings are thin

73
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:00,960
but this one's fat and red, see?

74
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:04,840
Must have been a good year
to be a tree.

75
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:09,160
I should have been relieved, you know.

76
00:05:09,440 --> 00:05:12,320
-Oh, Coal Hill School. Sleepover.
-Shh, shh!

77
00:05:13,160 --> 00:05:14,560
(KEYS JANGLING)

78
00:05:25,160 --> 00:05:26,320
(CHILDREN GROANING)

79
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:28,720
(BOY YAWNING)

80
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:30,160
(LOCK BEEPING)

81
00:05:32,800 --> 00:05:34,040
(DOOR CREAKING)

82
00:05:34,920 --> 00:05:36,680
Hang on. There's a knack to this.

83
00:05:37,360 --> 00:05:39,160
No, no, no, no, no. It moved. It moved.

84
00:05:39,240 --> 00:05:41,440
It's just jammed, it's not locked.
Come on, team.

85
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:42,800
What team?

86
00:05:44,280 --> 00:05:45,440
(ALL GRUNTING)

87
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:51,000
Wow!

88
00:05:51,480 --> 00:05:53,880
-BOY: Sir, where are we?
-What do you mean, where are we?

89
00:05:54,200 --> 00:05:55,920
(CHILDREN GASPING)

90
00:05:57,120 --> 00:05:59,640
We can't have been asleep
for that long, can we?

91
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:02,680
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

92
00:06:07,600 --> 00:06:09,160
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

93
00:06:19,440 --> 00:06:21,880
You've heard of leaves on the line.

94
00:06:21,960 --> 00:06:24,920
This is going to be slightly
harder to clear.

95
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,720
In three hours" time,
the Ghana Black Stars are due to play

96
00:06:27,800 --> 00:06:29,720
Sierra Leone
in the African Cup of Nations.

97
00:06:30,040 --> 00:06:32,200
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

98
00:06:34,320 --> 00:06:36,360
It does not look
like the pitch will be ready.

99
00:06:37,880 --> 00:06:39,640
You are always showing me
amazing things.

100
00:06:39,720 --> 00:06:43,280
Well, I, Doctor, have finally got
something amazing to show you.

101
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:45,600
Yes, well, there are some things
that I've never seen

102
00:06:45,920 --> 00:06:47,920
but that's usually because
I've chosen not to see them,

103
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,960
even my incredibly long life
is too short for Les Misérables.

104
00:06:51,040 --> 00:06:52,280
CLARA: Oh, Doctor.

105
00:06:52,760 --> 00:06:54,520
You are going to love this.

106
00:06:54,600 --> 00:06:56,400
DOCTOR: Well, when you come
to collect this child,

107
00:06:56,480 --> 00:06:57,720
you can tell me then.

108
00:06:58,160 --> 00:07:00,080
Huh? What child?

109
00:07:00,160 --> 00:07:02,880
Young female human.
Standard defenceless little girl.

110
00:07:03,640 --> 00:07:06,680
Your friend Mr Pink was supposed
to be looking after her.

111
00:07:07,040 --> 00:07:09,840
-She probably has a name.
-Good point.

112
00:07:11,520 --> 00:07:13,240
You. Have you got a name at all?

113
00:07:13,560 --> 00:07:15,160
Maebh. My name's Maebh.

114
00:07:15,440 --> 00:07:17,120
What? Maebh?

115
00:07:17,200 --> 00:07:19,120
-Where are you?
-Trafalgar Square.

116
00:07:19,200 --> 00:07:21,960
I found her wandering
around the brand new forest.

117
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:23,720
-Brand new forest?
-Yes.

118
00:07:23,800 --> 00:07:25,560
It's like the New Forest,
except even newer.

119
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:28,680
Is that the forest
that's covering London?

120
00:07:28,760 --> 00:07:30,720
DOCTOR: Was that the amazing thing
that you were going to show me?

121
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:32,600
'Tis amazing, but I saw it first.

122
00:07:33,720 --> 00:07:36,360
Look, is she all right?
Will you bring her over?

123
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:39,720
No, I can't bring her over.
I'm a Time Lord, not a childminder.

124
00:07:39,800 --> 00:07:42,600
You've got a spaceship.
All we've got are Oyster cards.

125
00:07:42,680 --> 00:07:47,200
And I've got a global rapid
afforestation crisis to deal with.

126
00:07:51,720 --> 00:07:53,440
-What did they say?
-Who?

127
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:55,680
School. Parents.
You were just on the phone.

128
00:07:56,320 --> 00:07:57,840
Oh, yeah. Rang school and parents.

129
00:07:57,920 --> 00:08:00,080
Yes, of course.
Thought that was the priority.

130
00:08:00,480 --> 00:08:01,600
And?

131
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:04,520
And I couldn't get through.
Left messages. I'll try again.

132
00:08:04,600 --> 00:08:06,720
Oh, you didn't call the school.
You called him.

133
00:08:07,120 --> 00:08:10,680
No, he called me, actually.
I can't stop him calling me, can I?

134
00:08:10,760 --> 00:08:12,080
I thought you weren't in contact.

135
00:08:13,960 --> 00:08:16,800
London has just been taken over
by a gigantic forest.

136
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:18,120
Who do you want to talk to, Monty Don?

137
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:20,760
I want to do my job,
which is looking after these kids.

138
00:08:20,840 --> 00:08:22,200
Oh, really? How many kids?

139
00:08:22,280 --> 00:08:24,240
-What?
-Where's Maebh Arden?

140
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:27,360
She's with the Doctor.

141
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:29,240
What? No, no, no, no.

142
00:08:29,320 --> 00:08:31,640
Maebh is a vulnerable kid.
She's on medication.

143
00:08:31,720 --> 00:08:35,000
She's had an emotional trauma.
He... Has he even been CRB checked?

144
00:08:35,080 --> 00:08:38,160
He didn't abduct her. She was lost.
He found her.

145
00:08:38,240 --> 00:08:39,560
I thought you said they were in love.

146
00:08:39,640 --> 00:08:41,200
Why are they shouting at each other?

147
00:08:41,280 --> 00:08:43,200
That's what people do
when they're in love.

148
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:44,680
Don't you know anything?

149
00:08:46,920 --> 00:08:49,680
BOY: Where are we actually going?
Where is he taking us?

150
00:08:49,760 --> 00:08:51,200
(CHILDREN GRUMBLING)

151
00:08:51,680 --> 00:08:53,360
-Who wants to be navigator?
-CHILDREN: Me, me, me!

152
00:08:53,440 --> 00:08:55,040
Good lad. Come on, let's do this.

153
00:08:55,120 --> 00:08:56,640
What's a navigator?

154
00:08:56,720 --> 00:08:59,680
We'll follow the lampposts,
that will keep us on Cromwell Road.

155
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:01,480
We'll be able to orientate ourselves.

156
00:09:01,560 --> 00:09:04,960
I thought we were getting a coach.
Where's the coach?

157
00:09:05,040 --> 00:09:08,080
Well, Ruby, it seems
there are a lot of trees in the way.

158
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,840
Why can't we just wait here
till they've gone?

159
00:09:10,920 --> 00:09:12,960
Trees don't just disappear, Ruby.

160
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:15,120
They just came.
Why wouldn't they just go?

161
00:09:15,480 --> 00:09:18,120
You see, the question is
how did it get here?

162
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:19,240
Can a forest grow overnight

163
00:09:19,320 --> 00:09:21,760
or have we been asleep for years,
like Sleeping Beauty?

164
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:24,440
No, the question is how are we
going to get these kids home?

165
00:09:24,840 --> 00:09:27,400
Oh, absolutely. Yeah.
That is the big question.

166
00:09:27,640 --> 00:09:30,040
DANNY: Okay, team!
It's crucial we stick together.

167
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:31,920
If you start to fall behind, don't.

168
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:33,720
Bradley, we're going to head
northeast first

169
00:09:33,800 --> 00:09:36,800
to collect Maebh from Trafalgar Square,
then we're going south to the river.

170
00:09:36,880 --> 00:09:38,080
Come on, keep up!

171
00:09:38,160 --> 00:09:39,960
-(CHILDREN MURMURING)
-BOY: What's he talking about?

172
00:09:40,520 --> 00:09:42,760
You are enjoying this
just a little bit too much.

173
00:09:42,840 --> 00:09:47,400
Come on, are you not even
a little bit curious about how?

174
00:09:47,480 --> 00:09:48,960
Who? Why? When?

175
00:09:49,040 --> 00:09:51,840
I am curious. I am bewildered.

176
00:09:51,920 --> 00:09:54,240
I am, in fact, enchanted.

177
00:09:54,320 --> 00:09:56,640
But I'm not the priority here.
The kids are.

178
00:09:56,720 --> 00:09:58,840
You see, now, that attitude is...

179
00:09:59,840 --> 00:10:01,720
actually very attractive.

180
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:04,160
The government emergency committee,
COBRA,

181
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:06,120
has formulated an action plan.

182
00:10:06,200 --> 00:10:08,160
We will create pathways
through the trees,

183
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:10,040
using carefully controlled fires.

184
00:10:10,120 --> 00:10:12,840
This will facilitate
the movement of essential services.

185
00:10:12,920 --> 00:10:14,560
We're therefore asking you
to stay in your homes...

186
00:10:14,640 --> 00:10:16,840
- (SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)
-...Till your baths, sinks

187
00:10:16,920 --> 00:10:18,720
and any buckets with fresh water...

188
00:10:18,840 --> 00:10:20,000
Why would there be no reading?

189
00:10:21,240 --> 00:10:23,560
Because they're actually
made of wood. No circuits.

190
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:25,480
No mechanism. Wood.

191
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:28,680
-(GRUNTS)
-What's this for?

192
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:31,960
This is a sonic screwdriver.

193
00:10:32,040 --> 00:10:34,880
It interacts with any form
of communication you care to mention.

194
00:10:34,960 --> 00:10:38,440
Sadly, trees have no moving parts
and they don't communicate.

195
00:10:38,520 --> 00:10:40,320
They communicate a bit, though.

196
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:42,120
What?

197
00:10:42,200 --> 00:10:44,720
Otherwise they wouldn't all grow
at the same time, would they?

198
00:10:45,360 --> 00:10:48,000
So, what, do you think
that's how spring begins?

199
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:50,040
With a group message on Tree Facebook?

200
00:10:50,120 --> 00:10:51,920
Do you think they send
texts to each other?

201
00:10:52,280 --> 00:10:54,560
You don't need a phone
to communicate, do you?

202
00:10:54,640 --> 00:10:57,720
I haven't phoned home and I know
my mum is worried about me.

203
00:11:03,360 --> 00:11:05,360
You said you'd collect Maebh!

204
00:11:05,680 --> 00:11:09,160
It's all right, I'm collecting her.
Soon as I find my car keys.

205
00:11:09,840 --> 00:11:12,080
I can't see a thing!

206
00:11:12,680 --> 00:11:16,120
Next door planted bloody
hydrangeas and they've gone mental!

207
00:11:16,520 --> 00:11:19,080
I've had words with her
about it before. She's...

208
00:11:20,600 --> 00:11:21,800
Oh.

209
00:11:22,960 --> 00:11:24,240
I'll call you back.

210
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:28,920
Miss, in the museum, right,
I was reading about reproduction...

211
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:30,600
Oh, Ruby, this really isn't
the right moment...

212
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:32,960
And that said that trees have blossom

213
00:11:33,040 --> 00:11:35,680
and then that turns into fruit
or seeds or nuts. Right?

214
00:11:35,760 --> 00:11:36,920
Right, Ruby.

215
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:39,760
This tree has got blossom and nuts.

216
00:11:39,840 --> 00:11:40,840
Oh, yeah.

217
00:11:41,520 --> 00:11:42,800
That is strange.

218
00:11:43,080 --> 00:11:45,800
Nuts. That's unfortunate for you,
isn't it, Bradley?

219
00:11:45,880 --> 00:11:47,240
You have an allergy, don't you?

220
00:11:47,320 --> 00:11:48,320
What if one of them falls on your head?

221
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:51,040
You'd die, Bradley, yeah?
Or you'd swell up like a massive melon.

222
00:11:51,120 --> 00:11:52,480
Shut it!

223
00:11:53,440 --> 00:11:54,880
I think we should have been consulted.

224
00:11:55,600 --> 00:11:57,360
What's it made of, even?

225
00:11:57,920 --> 00:11:59,400
MAEBH'S MUM: How far does this go?

226
00:11:59,480 --> 00:12:01,120
I need to collect Maebh.

227
00:12:02,840 --> 00:12:05,880
Trafalgar Square! Well done, Bradley.
Excellent navigation skills.

228
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:08,160
A-ha! There it is.
All sorted now. Come on.

229
00:12:08,440 --> 00:12:10,600
Can we take a picture
with the lion, sir? Please?

230
00:12:10,800 --> 00:12:12,600
Uh, stay together but okay.

231
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:15,760
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

232
00:12:16,560 --> 00:12:18,680
I cannot believe
Bradley just said "please”.

233
00:12:18,960 --> 00:12:20,360
-Really?
-Yeah.

234
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:23,280
He usually prefers
other means of persuasion.

235
00:12:23,680 --> 00:12:25,480
Give it! Give it!

236
00:12:25,800 --> 00:12:28,000
Miss! He won't lend me his dictionary.

237
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:30,000
You could try saying "please”, Bradley.

238
00:12:30,080 --> 00:12:31,680
-(BOY GROANING)
-(LOUD CRASH)

239
00:12:31,920 --> 00:12:32,920
(WHIMPERS)

240
00:12:34,640 --> 00:12:36,080
And Ruby...

241
00:12:36,840 --> 00:12:39,640
How do we find X?

242
00:12:41,160 --> 00:12:42,160
Ruby?

243
00:12:42,680 --> 00:12:44,640
It's there, sir. At the top.

244
00:12:45,240 --> 00:12:47,040
No, how do we find...

245
00:12:47,120 --> 00:12:50,680
It's not lost. It's there,
at the top, look!

246
00:12:51,080 --> 00:12:53,640
No, how do we find the value of X?

247
00:12:53,720 --> 00:12:56,160
Why are you asking me
all the questions?

248
00:12:56,240 --> 00:12:57,600
Give someone else a go.

249
00:12:57,760 --> 00:12:59,200
You bring out the best in them.

250
00:12:59,800 --> 00:13:00,960
-(RUMBLING)
-(CHILDREN WHIMPERING)

251
00:13:01,200 --> 00:13:02,800
BOY: Whoa! What was that?

252
00:13:02,960 --> 00:13:03,960
(SHRIEKS)

253
00:13:05,240 --> 00:13:08,160
Look, sir. No rings.

254
00:13:09,080 --> 00:13:12,200
Trees usually have rings,
to tell you how old they are.

255
00:13:12,280 --> 00:13:14,120
This one's got no rings.

256
00:13:14,360 --> 00:13:15,920
Why's that then, sir?

257
00:13:16,280 --> 00:13:18,560
The rings mark the years of growth.

258
00:13:19,120 --> 00:13:20,840
One ring for each year.

259
00:13:21,760 --> 00:13:23,000
This grew up overnight.

260
00:13:23,080 --> 00:13:24,360
That whole tree

261
00:13:24,440 --> 00:13:26,360
is the result
of just one night's growth.

262
00:13:26,440 --> 00:13:28,240
And they're still growing.

263
00:13:28,320 --> 00:13:31,760
Everyone, this is the Doctor
and he's going to sort everything out.

264
00:13:31,840 --> 00:13:33,800
Isn't that right, Doctor?
It's what he does.

265
00:13:33,880 --> 00:13:35,200
Well, having looked at things,

266
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:37,240
I think probably
the answer to that is no.

267
00:13:37,320 --> 00:13:38,880
He always says that.
He's really clever.

268
00:13:38,960 --> 00:13:40,560
Oh, yes, I am very clever.

269
00:13:40,640 --> 00:13:43,240
But what use is clever against trees?
They don't listen to reason.

270
00:13:43,320 --> 00:13:45,320
You can't plead with them.
You can't lie to them.

271
00:13:45,880 --> 00:13:47,880
They've got no moving parts,
no circuits.

272
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:49,600
This is a natural event.

273
00:13:49,680 --> 00:13:51,920
How can it be natural for a tree
to grow in one night?

274
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:55,080
Exactly what they said
about the Ice Age.

275
00:13:55,160 --> 00:13:58,080
How can whole glaciers
just pop up out of nowhere?

276
00:13:58,160 --> 00:13:59,520
Well, they just did.

277
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:03,880
That's how this planet grows.
A series of catastrophes.

278
00:14:04,240 --> 00:14:06,200
Farewell to the Ice Age.

279
00:14:06,440 --> 00:14:09,680
Welcome to the Tree Age. Possibly.

280
00:14:10,160 --> 00:14:13,320
When the Ice Age was here,
you lot managed to cook mammoth.

281
00:14:13,760 --> 00:14:15,760
Now that there's a forest,
you'll just have to eat nuts.

282
00:14:15,840 --> 00:14:17,800
I can't eat nuts. I've got an allergy.

283
00:14:18,280 --> 00:14:20,440
Don't worry. It's a thing he does.

284
00:14:20,520 --> 00:14:23,160
He pretends he's not interested
and then he has an idea.

285
00:14:23,400 --> 00:14:24,760
He's playing for time.

286
00:14:25,120 --> 00:14:26,440
Time!

287
00:14:28,040 --> 00:14:29,200
Interesting.

288
00:14:30,480 --> 00:14:32,080
See? Clever kicking in.

289
00:14:32,360 --> 00:14:34,480
A tree is a time machine.

290
00:14:34,560 --> 00:14:37,120
You plant a little acorn in 1795

291
00:14:37,200 --> 00:14:39,280
and in the year 2016
there's an oak tree,

292
00:14:39,480 --> 00:14:41,360
there, in the same spot,

293
00:14:41,440 --> 00:14:46,360
with a tiny little bit of 1795
still alive inside of it.

294
00:14:46,440 --> 00:14:50,640
You can't create a whole overnight
forest with extra-special fertilizer.

295
00:14:50,720 --> 00:14:53,160
You have to mess
with the fabric of time.

296
00:14:54,400 --> 00:14:57,000
And communicate with trees.

297
00:15:03,200 --> 00:15:04,920
So you're saying
it's an act of aggression?

298
00:15:05,720 --> 00:15:08,120
-By trees.
-Um, trees clean the air.

299
00:15:08,360 --> 00:15:10,280
Exactly. Well done, Ruby.

300
00:15:10,360 --> 00:15:12,640
Someone or something who's trying
to scrub the atmosphere

301
00:15:12,720 --> 00:15:15,120
before colonising or invading...

302
00:15:15,600 --> 00:15:17,560
Ah, yes, Doctor... (CLEARS THROAT)

303
00:15:17,640 --> 00:15:19,720
This is Coal Hill Year 8
Gifted and Talented group.

304
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:22,080
What are the round bits for?

305
00:15:22,400 --> 00:15:23,640
Ask your teacher. Come on!

306
00:15:23,720 --> 00:15:25,240
-Down from there! Hey!
-(CHILDREN MURMURING)

307
00:15:25,320 --> 00:15:27,120
Away from the console, come on.

308
00:15:27,200 --> 00:15:29,200
That's an antique. Get away from there!
Don't touch that!

309
00:15:29,280 --> 00:15:30,920
Haven't any of you been
struck by the fact that it's...

310
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:32,760
Look, it's bigger on the inside!

311
00:15:32,840 --> 00:15:35,120
There wasn't a forest,
then there was a forest.

312
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:36,960
Nothing surprises us any more.

313
00:15:37,480 --> 00:15:40,600
These trees all appeared at once.
That wasn't a coincidence.

314
00:15:41,080 --> 00:15:43,560
There's no such thing
as an arboreal coincidence.

315
00:15:44,240 --> 00:15:47,520
Something, someone
has coordinated this.

316
00:15:47,840 --> 00:15:49,760
To coordinate, you need to communicate.

317
00:15:49,840 --> 00:15:52,040
Every communication channel
on the Tardis is open

318
00:15:52,120 --> 00:15:54,240
and nothing.

319
00:15:56,240 --> 00:15:57,400
Except...

320
00:15:58,720 --> 00:16:00,080
Let me see that.

321
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:04,720
Homework books. Why are these here?

322
00:16:07,880 --> 00:16:09,440
Maebh Arden.

323
00:16:10,200 --> 00:16:12,200
Maebh Arden. Which one is Maebh Arden?

324
00:16:12,720 --> 00:16:13,880
Which one is Maebh?

325
00:16:13,960 --> 00:16:15,520
Maebh? Maebh?

326
00:16:16,640 --> 00:16:18,200
Maebh? Maebh?

327
00:16:19,960 --> 00:16:22,240
Maebh? Maebh? Maebh?

328
00:16:22,760 --> 00:16:25,040
-Maebh? Maebh?
-Oh, my God!

329
00:16:25,120 --> 00:16:28,400
Maebh's gone.
Maebh's lost in the forest.

330
00:16:28,480 --> 00:16:29,760
-Maebh's going to die!
-DOCTOR: Ahhh!

331
00:16:29,840 --> 00:16:31,640
Ruby, that's enough! Doctor?

332
00:16:31,720 --> 00:16:34,280
-We've got to find her!
-Yes, I know that we have to find her.

333
00:16:34,360 --> 00:16:35,920
Doctor, listen to me.

334
00:16:36,680 --> 00:16:38,400
Her sister went missing last year.

335
00:16:38,640 --> 00:16:40,600
She's on medication.
The child is barely functioning.

336
00:16:40,680 --> 00:16:42,160
She hears voices.

337
00:16:42,640 --> 00:16:45,280
-She's very vulnerable.
-What do the voices say?

338
00:16:45,360 --> 00:16:46,640
I don't know.
She takes tablets and they stop.

339
00:16:47,440 --> 00:16:49,200
You people, you never learn.

340
00:16:49,800 --> 00:16:52,720
If a child is speaking, listen to it!

341
00:16:52,800 --> 00:16:55,040
Oh, like you listened to her?

342
00:16:58,360 --> 00:16:59,720
He's right.

343
00:16:59,800 --> 00:17:01,920
She was trying to tell me
something and I ignored her.

344
00:17:02,200 --> 00:17:04,880
Maebh Arden is tuned
to a different channel.

345
00:17:04,960 --> 00:17:07,680
She can lead us to the source,
to the heart of the forest.

346
00:17:08,400 --> 00:17:10,160
We have to listen to her,
we have to find her.

347
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:12,080
Not everything can be fixed
with a screwdriver.

348
00:17:12,160 --> 00:17:13,200
It's not a magic wand.

349
00:17:13,280 --> 00:17:14,960
-Does she have a phone?
-Well, yeah, she does.

350
00:17:15,040 --> 00:17:16,880
-Have you got the number?
-Um, yep.

351
00:17:18,560 --> 00:17:21,400
Maebh Arden.
500 yards southeast of here.

352
00:17:22,400 --> 00:17:23,800
-I'll go get her.
-I'll go with him.

353
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:25,960
-Oh, I can go. You can...
-You haven't seen him for months?

354
00:17:26,960 --> 00:17:28,040
Something like that.

355
00:17:28,120 --> 00:17:30,440
You didn't even say hello.
You just sprung straight into action.

356
00:17:31,600 --> 00:17:32,760
Special unit.

357
00:17:32,840 --> 00:17:34,400
-BOY: This is so cool...
-Hey!

358
00:17:34,480 --> 00:17:36,440
Do not touch anything.

359
00:17:36,720 --> 00:17:39,040
-Anything. Okay?
-Okay.

360
00:17:39,720 --> 00:17:42,040
See? Someone needs to go.
Child protection.

361
00:17:42,320 --> 00:17:43,960
(CHILDREN MURMURING)

362
00:17:45,280 --> 00:17:47,000
Gifted and Talented? Really?

363
00:17:47,960 --> 00:17:50,640
Furious, fearful, tongue-tied...

364
00:17:51,120 --> 00:17:53,520
They're all superpowers
if you use them properly.

365
00:17:53,600 --> 00:17:54,800
Are they going to be all right?

366
00:17:54,880 --> 00:17:57,280
They're in the Tardis.
It's the safest place on the planet.

367
00:17:57,360 --> 00:17:58,520
(RUMBLING)

368
00:18:04,080 --> 00:18:05,640
(CLARA GRUNTS)

369
00:18:08,440 --> 00:18:09,880
(WINGS FLAPPING)

370
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:12,840
-If this is an invasion...
-What?

371
00:18:13,320 --> 00:18:15,960
It's over. They're here. They've won.

372
00:18:17,400 --> 00:18:18,960
What do they want?

373
00:18:22,560 --> 00:18:24,400
(ALL COUGHING)

374
00:18:25,360 --> 00:18:27,880
I'm not just going to stand here
and let her die!

375
00:18:28,200 --> 00:18:29,960
-Who?
-Miss.

376
00:18:30,040 --> 00:18:33,160
You let her go off
with some randomer into the forest.

377
00:18:33,560 --> 00:18:35,480
You're supposed to be
madly in love with her.

378
00:18:35,760 --> 00:18:37,200
I... Who said that?

379
00:18:37,560 --> 00:18:38,840
Everyone.

380
00:18:38,920 --> 00:18:40,560
She's probably dead now, anyway.
Crushed by Nelson.

381
00:18:41,440 --> 00:18:44,760
What if the trees collapse on her
and kill her?

382
00:18:44,960 --> 00:18:46,360
You're worrying too much.

383
00:18:46,440 --> 00:18:50,160
Yeah, but what if the wild animals
come out and eat her?

384
00:18:50,440 --> 00:18:52,920
Ruby, you're letting your
imagination run away with you.

385
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:54,080
I'm not, though, am I?

386
00:18:54,160 --> 00:18:56,360
Because I haven't got an imagination.

387
00:18:56,440 --> 00:18:58,320
You can ask Miss Oswald.

388
00:18:59,360 --> 00:19:01,560
Okay, then, come on, team.
Let's do this!

389
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:04,200
We will, if you stop calling us a team.

390
00:19:12,120 --> 00:19:13,400
Maebh!

391
00:19:21,080 --> 00:19:23,440
Doctor? Look behind us.

392
00:19:23,520 --> 00:19:26,040
The path we just walked down,
it's overgrown already.

393
00:19:26,120 --> 00:19:27,120
Clara!

394
00:19:32,280 --> 00:19:33,600
Why would she put her phone down?

395
00:19:33,680 --> 00:19:36,640
Doesn't want to be followed?
Lost a hold of it in a struggle?

396
00:19:36,720 --> 00:19:39,360
Left it as a clue,
so we would know where she was going?

397
00:19:39,440 --> 00:19:41,120
Trail of breadcrumbs.
Hansel and Gretel.

398
00:19:41,400 --> 00:19:42,800
I'm actually frightened.
I never get frightened.

399
00:19:42,880 --> 00:19:44,800
-Why am I frightened?
-You just lost a little girl.

400
00:19:44,880 --> 00:19:46,920
Yes. That is a worry
but I know you'll find her.

401
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:50,880
No, no, no. This, this is not a worry,
this is a dread. Maebh!

402
00:19:51,200 --> 00:19:53,400
You're pursuing a little lost girl
through a mysterious forest.

403
00:19:53,480 --> 00:19:55,040
The path has disappeared.

404
00:19:55,320 --> 00:19:59,520
You find yourself with a strangely
compelling, masculine figure...

405
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:01,000
Maebh!

406
00:20:01,080 --> 00:20:02,920
Any minute now, we're going
to find a gingerbread cottage

407
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:04,880
with a cannibal witch inside. Maebh!

408
00:20:05,040 --> 00:20:07,680
Exactly. The forest.

409
00:20:08,040 --> 00:20:10,120
It's in all the stories
that kept you awake at night.

410
00:20:10,680 --> 00:20:12,960
The forest is mankind's nightmare.

411
00:20:13,160 --> 00:20:14,720
(PANTING)

412
00:20:45,040 --> 00:20:46,960
(PANTING CONTINUES)

413
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:52,800
DOCTOR: Clara!

414
00:20:53,240 --> 00:20:54,280
Is it hers?

415
00:20:55,200 --> 00:20:57,040
Yes. Clever girl.

416
00:21:00,320 --> 00:21:02,760
Get back! We're burning here.
Stay back.

417
00:21:02,840 --> 00:21:04,960
-CLARA: We're looking for a little girl.
-Stay back.

418
00:21:05,320 --> 00:21:07,160
We're about to burn.

419
00:21:11,800 --> 00:21:12,960
MAN 1: Good job!

420
00:21:22,520 --> 00:21:23,520
MAN 2: What's going on?

421
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:25,440
MAN 3: Tree's not responding
to flamethrower.

422
00:21:25,520 --> 00:21:27,800
I mean, they don't catch fire.
They just don't catch.

423
00:21:27,880 --> 00:21:29,640
It's like they're flameproof
or something.

424
00:21:29,720 --> 00:21:31,360
Trees control the oxygen on this planet,

425
00:21:31,440 --> 00:21:33,200
they withhold it,
they smother the fire.

426
00:21:33,720 --> 00:21:35,200
What sort of forest is clever?
What sort of forest

427
00:21:35,280 --> 00:21:37,160
has its own in-built fire extinguisher?

428
00:21:37,240 --> 00:21:38,880
-CLARA: What do they want?
-And why now?

429
00:21:38,960 --> 00:21:39,960
What do you mean, why now?

430
00:21:40,040 --> 00:21:42,120
The whole natural order is
turning against this planet.

431
00:21:42,200 --> 00:21:44,320
-But why? Why now?
-Well, what else?

432
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:50,360
How did she know this?

433
00:21:52,440 --> 00:21:53,440
What is it?

434
00:21:53,640 --> 00:21:55,560
This is a massive solar flare
headed for Earth,

435
00:21:55,640 --> 00:21:57,720
like the one that destroyed
the Bank of Karabraxos.

436
00:21:57,800 --> 00:21:59,800
I've got an entire Tardis
and I didn't notice this.

437
00:22:00,040 --> 00:22:01,640
But she knew. How?

438
00:22:02,920 --> 00:22:04,720
This is Maebh's.
Where did you get this?

439
00:22:04,800 --> 00:22:06,320
You left your marking on the Tardis.

440
00:22:07,120 --> 00:22:09,280
Oh, great, right.
Well, that's just brilliant, isn't it?

441
00:22:09,360 --> 00:22:11,560
You don't think Danny saw this, do you?

442
00:22:11,800 --> 00:22:13,840
I've just informed you
that a solar flare

443
00:22:13,920 --> 00:22:15,160
is going to wipe out your planet.

444
00:22:15,240 --> 00:22:16,760
You're worried about
a row with your boyfriend?

445
00:22:16,840 --> 00:22:19,400
How does she know this?
She even put the date on it!

446
00:22:19,760 --> 00:22:20,960
I always make them date their homework.

447
00:22:21,360 --> 00:22:23,360
It's today's date!

448
00:22:29,520 --> 00:22:31,400
Well, there must be...

449
00:22:31,480 --> 00:22:32,720
a way.

450
00:22:33,880 --> 00:22:35,560
They want something.

451
00:22:36,040 --> 00:22:37,640
They're saying something.

452
00:22:38,280 --> 00:22:40,760
If there is a way,
the way is Maebh Arden.

453
00:22:41,720 --> 00:22:44,680
Okay, you know they're not really
gifted and talented, don't you?

454
00:22:44,760 --> 00:22:46,400
I just tell them that
to make them feel good.

455
00:22:46,720 --> 00:22:48,280
She's lost someone.
People who've lost someone,

456
00:22:48,360 --> 00:22:49,960
they're always listening,
they're always looking,

457
00:22:50,040 --> 00:22:51,160
they're always hoping.

458
00:22:51,240 --> 00:22:53,280
So they notice more. They hear more.

459
00:22:53,600 --> 00:22:55,440
(MOURNFUL HOWLING)

460
00:22:57,800 --> 00:22:58,920
Was that a howl?

461
00:22:59,520 --> 00:23:01,680
-(HOWLING CONTINUES)
-Was that a wolf?

462
00:23:03,760 --> 00:23:06,960
No. That is impossible.
We're in London.

463
00:23:07,040 --> 00:23:08,560
Would that be the London with the zoo?

464
00:23:08,640 --> 00:23:10,200
The zoo with the pack of wolves?

465
00:23:10,280 --> 00:23:12,080
The zoo whose barriers and gates

466
00:23:12,160 --> 00:23:13,840
have probably been
mangled by the trees?

467
00:23:13,920 --> 00:23:17,360
No, wolves are not impossible.

468
00:23:18,600 --> 00:23:20,600
Stick to the path, Red Riding Hood.

469
00:23:24,360 --> 00:23:25,880
There is no path.

470
00:23:25,960 --> 00:23:27,760
(HOWLING CONTINUES)

471
00:23:28,120 --> 00:23:29,520
Then we're lunch.

472
00:23:31,120 --> 00:23:33,080
(PANTING)

473
00:23:41,760 --> 00:23:44,080
(LOW GROWLING)

474
00:23:51,600 --> 00:23:53,520
(GROWLING CONTINUES)

475
00:24:06,160 --> 00:24:07,560
(SNARLING)

476
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:09,640
(SCREAMING)

477
00:24:10,720 --> 00:24:12,240
(SCREAMING IN DISTANCE)

478
00:24:12,320 --> 00:24:13,320
Maebh!

479
00:24:13,400 --> 00:24:14,480
(WOLVES SNARLING)

480
00:24:15,440 --> 00:24:16,440
(MAEBH PANTING)

481
00:24:41,320 --> 00:24:42,600
(WOLVES BARKING)

482
00:24:44,480 --> 00:24:47,480
Maebh! Doctor, give me a boost
so I can pull her over.

483
00:24:48,200 --> 00:24:51,040
-Maebh? Maebh?
-(WOLVES SNARLING)

484
00:24:53,480 --> 00:24:54,960
Maebh. You came looking for me.

485
00:24:55,320 --> 00:24:58,640
You didn't... Maebh, Maebh,
you didn't just stumble into the Tardis.

486
00:24:58,720 --> 00:25:00,600
-Tell me what you know.
-Doctor...

487
00:25:00,720 --> 00:25:01,800
-This is important.
-Yes,

488
00:25:01,880 --> 00:25:03,040
can we please deal
with the wolves first?

489
00:25:03,280 --> 00:25:05,880
These are zoo wolves,
they're not even used to hunting.

490
00:25:05,960 --> 00:25:08,120
-Doctor!
-(WOLVES SNARLING)

491
00:25:08,200 --> 00:25:09,560
Oh! Right, okay, all right, all right.

492
00:25:09,640 --> 00:25:11,920
We've just got to look as if
we're too much bother to eat.

493
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:13,600
Right. So stay still. Stay together.

494
00:25:13,680 --> 00:25:14,760
Look big. Look big,

495
00:25:14,840 --> 00:25:17,760
like a big, three-headed,
six-legged scary thing!

496
00:25:23,120 --> 00:25:24,520
(WOLVES WHINING)

497
00:25:25,160 --> 00:25:27,440
DOCTOR: (LAUGHING)
Told you they were rubbish.

498
00:25:28,120 --> 00:25:29,720
Those wolves are terrified.

499
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:32,560
What are wolves frightened of?

500
00:25:33,040 --> 00:25:35,200
(LOW GROWLING)

501
00:25:44,320 --> 00:25:45,800
(ROARS)

502
00:25:46,320 --> 00:25:48,360
There are very good,
solid, scientific reasons

503
00:25:48,440 --> 00:25:50,120
for being really quite frightened
just now.

504
00:25:50,600 --> 00:25:52,840
(ROARS)

505
00:25:53,400 --> 00:25:54,560
(SNARLING)

506
00:26:00,960 --> 00:26:01,960
(ROARS)

507
00:26:10,280 --> 00:26:11,280
(LAUGHING)

508
00:26:11,680 --> 00:26:12,680
(CHILDREN CHEERING)

509
00:26:15,160 --> 00:26:18,440
Mr Pink! Why, thank you very much.

510
00:26:18,520 --> 00:26:20,160
Ah, no problem.

511
00:26:20,240 --> 00:26:23,320
Just decided it was best
not to leave you alone with him.

512
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:25,120
They've worked well together.

513
00:26:25,200 --> 00:26:28,040
Noticeable increase
in confidence levels and energy.

514
00:26:28,120 --> 00:26:31,240
Well done.
And for saving us from a tiger, too.

515
00:26:31,600 --> 00:26:33,880
Um, has she had her medication yet?

516
00:26:33,960 --> 00:26:36,000
-Um, oh, no, I...
-No, no, not her medication.

517
00:26:36,080 --> 00:26:38,000
We don't want to shut her up.
We want to know what she knows.

518
00:26:38,400 --> 00:26:39,720
Maebh, what's... Maebh, what is...

519
00:26:39,800 --> 00:26:41,280
Maebh, what's this? What is this?

520
00:26:41,360 --> 00:26:43,640
Apart from being
almost savaged by a tiger

521
00:26:43,720 --> 00:26:45,120
and abducted by a Scotsman,

522
00:26:45,200 --> 00:26:47,160
she's allowed
any nervous tics she likes, okay?

523
00:26:47,240 --> 00:26:49,320
This is not a nervous tic.

524
00:26:49,400 --> 00:26:50,800
-This is react...
-RUBY: Please!

525
00:26:50,880 --> 00:26:52,280
Just give her her tablets!

526
00:26:52,800 --> 00:26:55,600
She's been in a state
since her sister went missing.

527
00:26:58,400 --> 00:27:01,080
Maebh! Maebh! Maebh!

528
00:27:01,160 --> 00:27:03,400
RUBY: You won't find
your sister out there.

529
00:27:03,480 --> 00:27:05,160
(MAEBH PANTING)

530
00:27:17,800 --> 00:27:20,240
Miss? What is it, miss?

531
00:27:21,320 --> 00:27:23,920
It's coming. It's coming
for everyone and I can't unthink it.

532
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,720
Maebh. Maebh,
this forest is communicating.

533
00:27:28,640 --> 00:27:29,760
With you. Nobody else.

534
00:27:29,840 --> 00:27:32,400
No technology can hear
what it's saying. But you can.

535
00:27:34,600 --> 00:27:35,720
Tell us what it wants.

536
00:27:36,040 --> 00:27:38,640
Where it came from.
Just tell me who did this.

537
00:27:44,040 --> 00:27:45,200
It was me.

538
00:27:45,680 --> 00:27:48,080
I did this. I did these trees.

539
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:50,920
No, Maebh.

540
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:54,160
You didn't make
a global forest appear overnight.

541
00:27:54,240 --> 00:27:55,440
How could you do that?

542
00:27:56,920 --> 00:27:58,320
Thoughts come to me.

543
00:27:58,400 --> 00:27:59,840
Ever since Annabel went missing,

544
00:27:59,920 --> 00:28:01,280
I look for her everywhere.

545
00:28:01,800 --> 00:28:05,960
I don't find her but I find thoughts.

546
00:28:06,040 --> 00:28:07,840
The big forest was one.

547
00:28:08,880 --> 00:28:10,720
I thought everyone would love it.

548
00:28:13,160 --> 00:28:14,280
The thoughts!

549
00:28:14,360 --> 00:28:15,800
(GROANS) The thoughts!

550
00:28:15,920 --> 00:28:17,080
They go so fast.

551
00:28:17,160 --> 00:28:18,360
This is stressing me now.

552
00:28:18,440 --> 00:28:20,760
When I get stressed,
I forget my anger management.

553
00:28:20,840 --> 00:28:24,120
Maebh, can you see
something that we can't see?

554
00:28:24,200 --> 00:28:26,600
Nearly... Too fast... Everywhere...

555
00:28:27,440 --> 00:28:29,240
Everything is subject to gravity.

556
00:28:29,680 --> 00:28:31,880
If I can create a little
local increase...

557
00:28:32,040 --> 00:28:33,920
No. You are not experimenting on...

558
00:28:35,600 --> 00:28:36,800
(GASPING)

559
00:28:37,080 --> 00:28:38,400
They're lovely!

560
00:28:40,560 --> 00:28:42,000
They don't like it
when you're holding them.

561
00:28:42,280 --> 00:28:43,400
They want you to let them go.

562
00:28:44,040 --> 00:28:45,280
Who are they?

563
00:28:47,360 --> 00:28:49,720
(DEEP VOICE JOINING MAEBH)
We are here. Here always,

564
00:28:49,800 --> 00:28:53,120
since the beginning and until the end.

565
00:28:54,520 --> 00:28:55,800
Here? That's it?

566
00:28:56,280 --> 00:28:59,200
We are the green shoots
that grow between the cracks,

567
00:28:59,520 --> 00:29:02,120
the grass that grows over
the mass graves.

568
00:29:02,360 --> 00:29:05,840
After your wars are over,
we will still be here.

569
00:29:06,040 --> 00:29:08,000
We are the life that prevails.

570
00:29:08,960 --> 00:29:10,480
Why now? Why are you here now?

571
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:13,120
We hear the call and we come,

572
00:29:13,320 --> 00:29:16,120
as we came before
to the great North Forest,

573
00:29:16,360 --> 00:29:18,920
where we lie still in a great circle,

574
00:29:19,240 --> 00:29:21,840
as we came to the vast Southern Forest.

575
00:29:23,160 --> 00:29:24,560
Who's calling you now?

576
00:29:25,080 --> 00:29:27,840
The sun that creates.
The sun that destroys.

577
00:29:27,920 --> 00:29:30,160
You are hurting us. Let us go.

578
00:29:31,160 --> 00:29:32,520
You sent for me.

579
00:29:32,600 --> 00:29:35,280
The girl came looking for me.
Why? Why me?

580
00:29:35,360 --> 00:29:37,920
We did not send...

581
00:29:38,440 --> 00:29:41,480
Pain. ...did not send for you.

582
00:29:42,200 --> 00:29:43,640
We don't know you.

583
00:29:44,120 --> 00:29:47,920
We were here before you
and will be here after you.

584
00:29:51,280 --> 00:29:52,280
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER CLICKS)
-Argh!

585
00:29:55,240 --> 00:29:57,160
That was actually quite cool.

586
00:29:57,560 --> 00:29:58,640
(GROANS)

587
00:30:01,320 --> 00:30:04,240
Maebh, you came looking
for the Doctor. Think.

588
00:30:04,520 --> 00:30:05,880
Who sent you for the Doctor?

589
00:30:06,240 --> 00:30:08,600
It was just a thought.
It was just a thought that came.

590
00:30:08,680 --> 00:30:09,840
I think it came from Miss.

591
00:30:13,920 --> 00:30:15,360
They've gone!

592
00:30:17,040 --> 00:30:18,840
Why does everything have to go?

593
00:30:30,800 --> 00:30:32,280
This really is
going to happen, isn't it?

594
00:30:32,680 --> 00:30:34,360
Stars implode. Planets grow cold.

595
00:30:34,440 --> 00:30:37,040
Catastrophe is the metabolism
of the universe.

596
00:30:37,120 --> 00:30:38,760
I can fight monsters.
I can't fight physics.

597
00:30:38,840 --> 00:30:41,080
Why would trees want to kill us?
We love trees.

598
00:30:41,680 --> 00:30:44,000
You've been chopping them down
for furniture for centuries.

599
00:30:44,080 --> 00:30:46,560
If that's love, no wonder they're
calling down fire from the heavens.

600
00:30:47,360 --> 00:30:48,920
But we saw the future.

601
00:30:49,600 --> 00:30:50,920
Lots of futures.

602
00:30:51,280 --> 00:30:52,760
Earth's futures!

603
00:30:54,400 --> 00:30:56,000
They're about to be erased.

604
00:31:01,640 --> 00:31:03,680
If you can't save them all,
save what you can.

605
00:31:06,920 --> 00:31:07,960
The Tardis.

606
00:31:08,920 --> 00:31:10,440
It's a lifeboat, isn't it?

607
00:31:12,040 --> 00:31:13,480
Not everybody has to die.

608
00:31:17,400 --> 00:31:19,240
(RUMBLING)

609
00:31:22,560 --> 00:31:24,360
DANNY: # Everywhere we go-o!

610
00:31:24,440 --> 00:31:26,200
CHILDREN: # Everywhere we go-o!

611
00:31:26,280 --> 00:31:27,960
# People wanna kno-ow!

612
00:31:28,040 --> 00:31:29,920
# People wanna kno-ow!

613
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:31,840
# Who we a-are

614
00:31:31,920 --> 00:31:33,720
CHILDREN: # Who we a-are

615
00:31:33,800 --> 00:31:37,440
DANNY: # We are the Coal Hill
Gifted and Talented

616
00:31:37,520 --> 00:31:40,560
CHILDREN: # We are the Coal Hill
Gifted and Talented... #

617
00:31:43,040 --> 00:31:44,040
Whoa!

618
00:31:44,280 --> 00:31:45,680
All right. Come on, team.

619
00:31:49,920 --> 00:31:52,080
When they're done,
you need to get in your box and go.

620
00:31:52,520 --> 00:31:54,040
DOCTOR: We're all going.
We're taking the kids.

621
00:31:54,240 --> 00:31:55,680
Taking them where?

622
00:31:55,760 --> 00:31:57,000
What are you going do with them?

623
00:31:57,520 --> 00:31:58,840
Leave them on an asteroid?

624
00:31:58,920 --> 00:32:00,720
Find a space academy
for the gifted and talented?

625
00:32:00,800 --> 00:32:02,720
They just want their mum and dads

626
00:32:03,160 --> 00:32:04,760
and they're never
going to stop wanting them.

627
00:32:05,360 --> 00:32:06,640
(CHILDREN GRUNTING)

628
00:32:08,160 --> 00:32:09,800
I can save you and Danny.

629
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:12,320
Danny Pink will never leave those kids
so long as he is breathing.

630
00:32:12,440 --> 00:32:14,600
-(CHILDREN CHEERING)
-Hey! Well done, team.

631
00:32:14,680 --> 00:32:16,280
BRADLEY: Can we take
another selfie, sir?

632
00:32:16,360 --> 00:32:18,040
DANNY: Course. Come on, then.
BOYS: Yes!

633
00:32:23,960 --> 00:32:25,280
I can save you.

634
00:32:26,200 --> 00:32:27,520
I don't want you to.

635
00:32:28,280 --> 00:32:31,200
-What, you don't want to live?
-Of course I want to live, I just...

636
00:32:33,280 --> 00:32:34,280
What?

637
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:36,400
Don't make me say it.

638
00:32:36,560 --> 00:32:37,680
Say what?

639
00:32:39,760 --> 00:32:41,560
I don't want to be the last of my kind.

640
00:32:47,800 --> 00:32:49,480
Then why did you bring us all here?

641
00:32:52,080 --> 00:32:54,680
Because it's the only way
to get you back to the Tardis,

642
00:32:55,480 --> 00:32:57,000
make you think you're saving someone.

643
00:32:57,840 --> 00:32:59,640
Well, you know what, Doctor?

644
00:32:59,880 --> 00:33:02,920
This time, the human race is saving you.

645
00:33:05,920 --> 00:33:07,240
Make it worthwhile.

646
00:33:10,360 --> 00:33:12,680
This is my world, too.

647
00:33:14,160 --> 00:33:17,600
I walk your Earth, I breathe your air.

648
00:33:19,360 --> 00:33:21,720
And on behalf of this world,
you're very welcome.

649
00:33:22,960 --> 00:33:24,200
Now, go.

650
00:33:25,800 --> 00:33:27,280
Save the next one.

651
00:33:35,440 --> 00:33:36,680
Maebh!

652
00:33:40,800 --> 00:33:43,840
I'm sorry that I couldn't help you.

653
00:33:44,520 --> 00:33:46,880
You helped me loads!
I thought it was all my fault.

654
00:33:46,960 --> 00:33:48,600
I feel much better now.

655
00:33:48,680 --> 00:33:50,200
Are you going to get rid of the forest?

656
00:33:56,400 --> 00:33:59,280
Hard to get rid of a flameproof forest,
Maebh, eh? Come on.

657
00:34:09,600 --> 00:34:11,080
SAMSON: Government crews
have been deployed...

658
00:34:11,160 --> 00:34:13,560
-(DOOR CLOSES)
-...with the latest de-fo...

659
00:34:14,080 --> 00:34:15,680
...de-foo...

660
00:34:15,760 --> 00:34:17,600
-(LAUGHTER)
-(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

661
00:34:18,280 --> 00:34:20,320
Defoliant agents, Samson.

662
00:34:20,680 --> 00:34:23,120
They're used to take the leaves off
the trees so they're easier to burn.

663
00:34:23,200 --> 00:34:24,200
That's harsh.

664
00:34:24,320 --> 00:34:25,920
(WHOOSHING)

665
00:34:26,600 --> 00:34:27,840
BOY: Where's he going?

666
00:34:29,560 --> 00:34:30,840
Home.

667
00:34:33,080 --> 00:34:34,400
He's going home.

668
00:34:36,440 --> 00:34:38,400
Which is exactly where we're going.

669
00:34:48,200 --> 00:34:49,920
Flameproof forest...

670
00:34:54,360 --> 00:34:57,640
Flameproof.. forest!

671
00:34:57,920 --> 00:35:00,360
A thousand atom bombs and no one hurt.

672
00:35:03,080 --> 00:35:05,600
I am Doctor Idiot!

673
00:35:06,600 --> 00:35:09,640
DOCTOR: Clara! Come back here!
Come back!

674
00:35:10,360 --> 00:35:12,520
-He's calling you.
-Yes, let him call.

675
00:35:12,600 --> 00:35:13,920
This is more important.

676
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:17,680
Clara! Mr Pink! Maebh!

677
00:35:17,760 --> 00:35:23,760
All of you! Quick! Quick!
Come back, come back. Come on!

678
00:35:24,120 --> 00:35:26,600
Maebh, quick! Good girl, good girl!
Come on!

679
00:35:29,200 --> 00:35:33,240
It's there on the screen, look!
Big solar flare. Headed this way.

680
00:35:33,320 --> 00:35:36,920
A thousand kilometres a second.
Coronal mass ejection.

681
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:38,760
Geomagnetic storm. It's huge!

682
00:35:39,280 --> 00:35:40,440
It's brewing up a solar wind

683
00:35:40,520 --> 00:35:42,720
big enough to blow
this whole planet away.

684
00:35:48,480 --> 00:35:51,680
I assumed your teachers
have mentioned this?

685
00:35:52,040 --> 00:35:54,880
I thought it would spoil
an otherwise enjoyable walk.

686
00:35:55,880 --> 00:35:57,600
Okay. Okay.

687
00:35:59,240 --> 00:36:02,240
Well, this is the bad news.

688
00:36:02,320 --> 00:36:04,360
The good news is it's happened before.

689
00:36:06,800 --> 00:36:10,600
And you're still here!
The Tunguska Blast, 1908,

690
00:36:10,840 --> 00:36:13,160
that should have blown
the whole planet off its axis.

691
00:36:13,240 --> 00:36:15,600
But it didn't.
It knocked a few trees over.

692
00:36:15,680 --> 00:36:17,560
Well, a few tens of thousands
of trees over.

693
00:36:17,640 --> 00:36:19,720
Curuca in Brazil. Same story.

694
00:36:19,800 --> 00:36:22,360
Earth should have been smashed!
But it wasn't.

695
00:36:22,520 --> 00:36:24,920
What do these things have in common?

696
00:36:25,800 --> 00:36:28,520
They're really, really scaring us?

697
00:36:29,560 --> 00:36:30,800
Trees!

698
00:36:31,240 --> 00:36:35,320
Whenever there's a planet-threatening,
extra-terrestrial impact, trees!

699
00:36:35,680 --> 00:36:38,640
Massive forest,
filling the atmosphere with oxygen.

700
00:36:38,880 --> 00:36:42,600
Pumping it up, like a massive,
highly inflammable airbag,

701
00:36:42,680 --> 00:36:43,920
so that when trouble hits...

702
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:45,160
Everyone dies.

703
00:36:45,240 --> 00:36:48,520
No. The impact burns off
the excess oxygen.

704
00:36:48,920 --> 00:36:52,040
You have some fairly hectic weather
for a few days

705
00:36:52,200 --> 00:36:54,400
and some fairly trippy-looking sunsets

706
00:36:54,800 --> 00:36:58,720
but apart from that,
you will be all right.

707
00:36:58,880 --> 00:37:04,440
I was wrong. The trees are not
your enemy. They're your shield.

708
00:37:04,840 --> 00:37:07,000
They've been saving you since forever,

709
00:37:07,360 --> 00:37:10,480
protecting you from everything
that space can throw at you.

710
00:37:10,720 --> 00:37:12,080
The wide ring.

711
00:37:15,200 --> 00:37:16,480
The red ring.

712
00:37:16,920 --> 00:37:18,920
In the museum,
Ruby saw a cross-section of a tree.

713
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:21,160
One of the rings was
wider than the others and red.

714
00:37:21,240 --> 00:37:24,040
Atmospheric dust,
captured by the trees.

715
00:37:24,120 --> 00:37:25,800
The fingerprint of an asteroid.

716
00:37:25,880 --> 00:37:27,440
Happy Red Ring Day.

717
00:37:27,520 --> 00:37:28,800
RUBY: I don't get it.

718
00:37:28,920 --> 00:37:31,560
If they're good, then why are we
chopping them down?

719
00:37:32,640 --> 00:37:34,920
The Government are sending out
defoliating teams.

720
00:37:35,080 --> 00:37:37,760
They're dropping chemicals on them
right now.

721
00:37:38,440 --> 00:37:40,120
What is it with you people?

722
00:37:40,200 --> 00:37:42,160
You hear voices,
you want to shut them up.

723
00:37:42,240 --> 00:37:44,560
The trees come to save you,
you want to chop them down.

724
00:37:44,640 --> 00:37:45,920
CLARA: Or you think you
need to save the world

725
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:47,680
when it's already saving itself.

726
00:37:47,760 --> 00:37:49,160
-I did admit that I was wrong.
-(BEEPING)

727
00:37:49,240 --> 00:37:50,240
(WHIRRING)

728
00:37:50,560 --> 00:37:53,640
Excellent.
Mobile networks are still operative.

729
00:37:54,480 --> 00:37:58,120
Right, we are going to call
everyone on Earth

730
00:37:58,200 --> 00:38:00,280
and tell them to leave the trees alone.

731
00:38:03,040 --> 00:38:04,040
Can I do it?

732
00:38:05,040 --> 00:38:08,480
I started it. I should finish it.

733
00:38:09,560 --> 00:38:13,040
Okay. Okay.

734
00:38:13,400 --> 00:38:16,480
Class project. Save the Earth.

735
00:38:17,720 --> 00:38:20,720
(CHILDREN CONFERRING, INDISTINCT)

736
00:38:25,440 --> 00:38:28,640
Okay. And I think that's it.

737
00:38:29,880 --> 00:38:30,920
(CLICKS)

738
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:33,840
(MOBILES RINGING)

739
00:38:34,720 --> 00:38:36,920
(RINGING ECHOES)

740
00:38:38,600 --> 00:38:41,200
(MOBILE RINGING)

741
00:38:43,120 --> 00:38:45,480
MAEBH: "Essential services
have been disrupted

742
00:38:45,560 --> 00:38:48,920
-"due to an unexpected forest.”
-Maebh! Where are you?

743
00:38:49,440 --> 00:38:50,560
"We'd like to reassure you

744
00:38:50,640 --> 00:38:53,280
"that the situation
will be rectified very soon.

745
00:38:53,680 --> 00:38:55,200
"Please don't be scared.

746
00:38:55,280 --> 00:38:58,280
"And please don't chop,
spray or harm the trees.

747
00:38:58,360 --> 00:39:02,480
"They're here to help.
Be less scared. Be more trusting.”

748
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:06,240
Oh, and Annabel Arden,

749
00:39:06,320 --> 00:39:07,640
please come home.

750
00:39:08,320 --> 00:39:11,120
-(POWERING DOWN)
-Okay, who would like to witness

751
00:39:11,200 --> 00:39:14,640
a once-in-a-billion years
solar event at close quarters?

752
00:39:15,600 --> 00:39:17,480
Mum! There's my mum!

753
00:39:25,480 --> 00:39:27,280
I thought I'd lost you, too.

754
00:39:29,040 --> 00:39:32,040
Never. Not ever.

755
00:39:32,360 --> 00:39:33,360
(LAUGHING)

756
00:39:35,080 --> 00:39:36,480
So, trip to space, anyone?

757
00:39:36,560 --> 00:39:37,720
I want my mum.

758
00:39:37,800 --> 00:39:39,440
I slightly want my mum, too.

759
00:39:39,800 --> 00:39:42,080
Tell them, Mr Pink,
what an educational opportunity...

760
00:39:42,160 --> 00:39:44,320
You... You go. This...

761
00:39:45,400 --> 00:39:47,160
This is enough for me.

762
00:39:47,880 --> 00:39:49,160
What?

763
00:39:50,920 --> 00:39:53,560
Coronal ejections, geomagnetic storms.

764
00:39:53,640 --> 00:39:55,440
How often do you get
a playlist like that?

765
00:39:56,000 --> 00:39:59,320
I was a soldier. I put myself at risk.

766
00:39:59,640 --> 00:40:03,920
I didn't try too hard to survive
but somehow, here I am.

767
00:40:06,600 --> 00:40:09,840
And now I can see what I nearly lost.
And it's enough.

768
00:40:11,120 --> 00:40:12,320
I don't want to see more things.

769
00:40:12,400 --> 00:40:15,560
I want to see the things
that are in front of me more clearly.

770
00:40:16,320 --> 00:40:18,840
There are wonders here, Clara Oswald.

771
00:40:19,600 --> 00:40:21,600
Bradley saying "please”,
that's a wonder.

772
00:40:22,160 --> 00:40:24,600
One person is more amazing,

773
00:40:24,680 --> 00:40:29,040
harder to understand,
but more amazing than universes.

774
00:40:29,120 --> 00:40:31,800
Really? What person is that, then?

775
00:40:34,400 --> 00:40:35,440
(KIDS CHEERING)

776
00:40:37,200 --> 00:40:40,800
I told you! I said so, didn't I?

777
00:40:41,600 --> 00:40:42,600
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

778
00:40:42,760 --> 00:40:44,400
CLARA: We could have a picnic.

779
00:40:44,640 --> 00:40:46,800
You can't. You've got marking.

780
00:40:48,640 --> 00:40:50,000
Oh.

781
00:40:50,520 --> 00:40:52,920
Well, no, no, no.
That was, um, that was from ages ago.

782
00:40:53,000 --> 00:40:54,080
You see, what happened was...

783
00:40:54,160 --> 00:40:57,680
They always write the date
neatly at the top of the page.

784
00:40:57,760 --> 00:40:59,440
Yeah, they do, don't they?

785
00:40:59,520 --> 00:41:01,120
Yeah, last Friday.

786
00:41:01,720 --> 00:41:03,600
You were on the Tardis last Friday.

787
00:41:04,040 --> 00:41:05,880
Today, you thought the world
was going to end.

788
00:41:05,960 --> 00:41:08,720
-You still didn't tell me the truth.
-No, I tried. He interrupted.

789
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:12,040
I just want to know the truth.
I don't care what it is.

790
00:41:12,120 --> 00:41:13,480
I just want to know it.

791
00:41:13,560 --> 00:41:15,480
Like Maebh said. Like the forest.

792
00:41:15,920 --> 00:41:18,360
Fear a little bit less,
trust a bit more.

793
00:41:19,320 --> 00:41:20,320
Okay.

794
00:41:22,520 --> 00:41:25,200
-Well...
-No, not now.

795
00:41:25,560 --> 00:41:28,360
Go home, do your marking.
Think about it.

796
00:41:28,440 --> 00:41:30,040
Then tell me.

797
00:41:30,800 --> 00:41:33,240
I saved you from a tiger today.
I deserve at least that.

798
00:41:35,120 --> 00:41:36,280
Yes, you did.

799
00:41:37,520 --> 00:41:40,160
And yes, you do.

800
00:41:51,800 --> 00:41:53,320
I hope I'm right.

801
00:41:53,880 --> 00:41:54,880
It would be slightly awkward

802
00:41:54,960 --> 00:41:56,760
if the world was destroyed
at this point.

803
00:41:57,080 --> 00:41:58,400
What?

804
00:41:59,280 --> 00:42:01,320
(RUMBLING)

805
00:42:04,360 --> 00:42:06,240
DOCTOR: There goes
the planet-sized airbag.

806
00:42:07,360 --> 00:42:10,840
That's the trees,
harvesting the solar fire.

807
00:42:22,080 --> 00:42:24,800
Now, that was surprising.

808
00:42:27,480 --> 00:42:30,080
And I love surprises.

809
00:42:40,480 --> 00:42:43,200
(CHIRPING, FLUTTERING)

810
00:42:44,560 --> 00:42:46,600
CLARA: That is amazing.

811
00:42:56,120 --> 00:42:58,040
How will they explain this tomorrow?

812
00:42:58,440 --> 00:43:00,520
You'll all forget it ever happened.

813
00:43:02,120 --> 00:43:04,720
We are not going to forget
an overnight forest.

814
00:43:04,800 --> 00:43:06,240
You forgot the last time.

815
00:43:07,080 --> 00:43:10,160
You remembered the fear
and you put it into fairy stories.

816
00:43:11,400 --> 00:43:14,600
It's a human superpower, forgetting.

817
00:43:14,960 --> 00:43:18,680
If you remembered how things felt,
you'd have stopped having wars.

818
00:43:19,360 --> 00:43:21,480
And stopped having babies.

819
00:43:30,760 --> 00:43:31,920
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

820
00:44:01,040 --> 00:44:02,840
Annabel!

821
00:44:02,960 --> 00:44:04,360
My Annabel!

822
00:44:05,120 --> 00:44:08,360
I knew you'd be here.
The thought of you came to me.

823
00:44:20,040 --> 00:44:23,200
DOCTOR: Clara?
CLARA: Do I have your attention?

824
00:44:23,440 --> 00:44:25,360
You will never step inside
your Tardis again.

825
00:44:27,160 --> 00:44:28,240
DOCTOR: Clara, what are you doing?

826
00:44:28,320 --> 00:44:29,720
CLARA: Time can be rewritten.

827
00:44:38,160 --> 00:44:40,640
DOCTOR: Clara, my Clara,
I don't think you will!

828
00:44:40,720 --> 00:44:41,720
You know who I am.

829
00:44:41,840 --> 00:44:45,240
I'm not Clara Oswald.
Clara Oswald has never existed.

